qx|6., wide|cs|6|ht|b|fp|1|at|^-{          The Keycard-Ask and Response Structure          
Summary}
^-|fp||at|^B@2
The Key card Ask is always 4 of the next higher suit after the agreed trump suit; responses are in steps following the traditional Roman Keycard response structure, 0 or 3, 1 or 4, 2 or 5 without, 2 or 5 with:


^BTrump Suit                   ^kSpades   ^NHearts ^PDiamonds ^rClubs
^bKickback Keycard Ask                  ^k4N        ^N4@S    ^P4@H     ^r4@D
^BResponses
^C1st Step: 0 or 3             ^k5@C        ^N4N     ^P4@S     ^r4@H
^C2nd Step: 1 or 4             ^k5@D        ^N5@C     ^P4N     ^r4@S
^C3rd Step: 2 or 5, no Queen   ^k5@H        ^N5@D     ^P5@C     ^r4N
^C4th Step: 2 or 5, with Queen ^k5@S        ^N5@H     ^P5@D     ^r5@C
|
PG| ***** 56 ***** |


AT|

With Kickback Keycard Ask, instead of a fixed suit-independent 4N ask, the Kickback Keycard Ask is 4 of the next higher suit after the trump suit. When the trump suit is Spades, 4N asks, and the responses are the familiar Keycard responses. When the trump suit is other than Spades, the adjusted Kickback Keycard Ask permits a full range of responses ending at 5 of the trump suit. Therefore, the contract level is never elevated purely because of system requirements. |
PG| ***** 57 ***** |


AT|

Explanation of treating voids, King and Queen asks are out side the scope of this work. Please refer to "A Better Control-Asking System" PDF file by Norman Pestaina |CP|1|AT|^*Hhttp://users.cis.fiu.edu/~pestaina/Kickback.pdf^*N|CP||at|.|
